<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2013/12/04/5-facts-about-the-minimum-wage/">About half</a> of all workers in the United States who are at or below the federal minimum wage of $7.25 an hour are ages 16 to 24. Would a higher minimum wage help young people get ahead? Would it help lift families out of poverty? Or would it unintentionally have the opposite effect by dampening hiring? Economists <a href="//www.econlife.com/minimum-wage-insight/">disagree</a> about the effects of a higher minimum wage. What do you think?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Is the minimum wage too low? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In &#8220;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/01/01/business/hourly-minimum-wage-is-going-up-for-millions.html">Statesâ Minimum Wages Rise, Helping Millions of Workers</a>,&#8221; Rachel Abrams writes about minimum wage increases that went into effect in 20 states this year:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-155080"></span></p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
For some low-wage workers, everyday tasks like spending money for bus fare to get to and from work also involve deciding which bill to pay or delay, or what to give up.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Rita Diaz, 26, who works two low-wage jobs, sometimes walks the three miles home from her job serving chicken at a Popeyeâs fast-food restaurant in Roslindale, Mass., when she doesnât have money for all of her expenses. Her plight is one of many highlighted by labor advocates who have been pushing for higher minimum wage levels.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In January, with an increase in the minimum wage in Massachusetts taking effect â raising hourly pay to $9 from $8 an hour â Ms. Diaz envisions being able to walk less and ride more.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI need to make a decision to buy clothes, or pay the rent or pay my cellphone bill,â she said. âNow Iâve got to do that decision, but Iâm going to have more money for me, too. A little bit of money for me.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By Thursday, minimum wage increases will go into effect in 20 states, including Massachusetts, as well as in the District of Columbia. A few other states will enact a pay bump later in the year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">All told, 29 states will exceed the federal minimum wage of $7.25 an hour at the beginning of January, according to the National Conference of State Legislatures.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The initial changes will enhance minimum pay by as little as a few pennies to as much as $1.25 an hour, affecting about 3.1 million employees, according to the Economic Policy Institute, a liberal research group.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThatâs going to be unnoticeable, really,â Gary Burtless, an economist at the Brookings Institution, said of some of the smaller changes, like the extra 12 cents an hour in Florida and 15 cents an hour in Missouri. âIf youâre talking about an increase of a buck or two bucks, then maybe thereâs some kind of noticeable effect.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nine states are increasing their minimum wage levels through automatic adjustments for cost-of-living expenses and other economic factors. Increases in the other states occurred through legislative or ballot changes. Over all, the new laws will cover about 60 percent of the nationâs work force, according to the Economic Policy Institute.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf youâre only making 15 or 16 thousand dollars year, an extra two grand is quite a bit of money,â said David Cooper, an economic analyst at the institute.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The smaller of the automatic increases in nine states will raise wages for about 4 to 7 percent of the lowest-paid workers, according to the institute, while the bigger increases will affect more. Nearly one-fifth of all wage earners in Minnesota will see a bump in pay when the wage floor jumps by $1 later in the year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About 3.3 million people earn the federal minimum wage or less, according to the United States Bureau of Labor Statistics.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the wealth gap between the rich and poor has expanded, the battle over wages for some of Americaâs lowest-paid workers has intensified.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The federal minimum wage has not been increased since 2007. President Obama has proposed raising it to $10.10 an hour, but that effort has stalled in Congress.
</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students:</strong> Read the entire article, then tell us &#8230;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â Is the minimum wage too low? Should the government raise the minimum wage as a way to fight poverty and help working families?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â What would you raise it to, given that the current federal minimum wage is $7.25 an hour? For example, the Obama administration is <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/03/us/politics/president-heads-to-michigan-to-press-minimum-wage-increase.html">asking for a $10.10 minimum wage</a>. Seattle has approved a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/us/seattle-approves-15-minimum-wage-setting-a-new-standard-for-big-cities.html">$15 minimum wage</a>. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2014/06/04/can-the-minimum-wage-be-too-high">How high is too high?</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â Does a higher minimum wage lift families out of poverty? Does it ultimately strengthen the economy by increasing workers&#8217; spending power? Or would a higher minimum wage force employers to hire fewer workers &#8212; leading to more unemployment? Economists and politicians disagree. What is your reasoning or evidence?</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students 13 and older</strong> are invited to comment below. Please use only your <strong>first name.</strong> For <a href="//www.nytimes.com/ref/membercenter/help/privacysummary.html">privacy policy</a> reasons, we will not publish student comments that include a last name.</p>
